Augustus himself com· posed a historical work on this subject, and we cannot fail to per· ceive that Livy wrote under the influence of the Augustan court He treats Marcellus as a favourite hero, and even in Plutarch we can trace the preference accorded to Marcellus. If we deduct all that family conceit and national pride have invented about Marcellus there remains indeed the image of a genuine Roman of the old type, of an intrepid soldier and an energetic officer.
